nly six years younger than Pierpont. The two were uncle and nephew but more like brothers in age."},{"number":4,"category":"character","header":"First Grand Master of Masons in Connecticut","body":"He was a Freemason in Hiram Lodge No. 1 in New Haven and became the first Grand Master of the Grand Lodge of Connecticut. The Grand Lodge still honors distinguished members with a medal in his name."},{"number":5,"category":"career","header":"Bought Richfield Township in Ohio's Western Reserve","body":"He invested £60,000 in the Connecticut Land Company in 1795 — five percent of the company — and was one of seven investors who purchased Richfield Township in Ohio. He sent his son John Stark Edwards as his first agent in the Western Reserve."}],"number_of_marriages":1,"cross_connections":[{"type":"civic_connection","related_id":"HD2925","display_label":"Newton settled the Ohio township he had bought.","link_text":"John Newton"},{"type":"historical_connection","related_id":"H00443","display_label":"Both Hooker descendants shaped the Western Reserve — land and education","link_text":"Rev. Giles Hooker Cowles"},{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"T00387","display_label":"He won this seat — then declined it, forcing Wadsworth back","link_text":"Col. Jeremiah Wadsworth"},{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"X00614","display_label":"Fellow early Connecticut lawyer-judge; husband of Edwards's niece Sally Burr.","link_text":"Judge Tapping Reeve"}],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","relationship":"portrait_subject","institution_blurb":"Yale University Art Gallery holds his 1795 portrait by William Jennys (ART031, accession 1968.30.4)."},{"institution_id":"INST0045"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Pierpont Edwards","first_name":"Pierpont","last_name":"Edwards","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/9d/William_Jennys_-_Portrait_of_Judge_Pierpont_Edwards_%281750-1826%29_-_1968.30.4_-_Yale_University_Art_Gallery.jpg"},"residence":{},"baptism":{